          .hex #cf7419

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Construction
      p Florida statute doesn’t specify a proportion for the flag beyond conforming to “standard commercial sizes.” It is usually produced with a proportion of 2:3.
      p It is required that the seal be 1/2 the width of the hoist and the red bars be 1/5 the hoist.
    .visual
      +construction(name, path)

  .guide.wide.timeline
    .content
      h2 Previous iterations
      ul.visual.flag-list
        li.flag-item
          span.flag: img.border(src='/assets/images/flag-florida-1845.svg', alt='Florida flag from 1845')
          h4 1845
          p Although never officially adopted, the Moseley flag flew at Governor William D. Moseley’s inauguration in 1845.
        li.flag-item
          span.flag: img.border(src='/assets/images/flag-florida-1861-1865.svg', alt='Florida flag from 1861')
          h4 1861-1865
          p Adopted by Governor Madison S. Perry when Florida seceded from the Union in 1861.
        li.flag-item
          span.flag: img.border(src='/assets/images/flag-florida-1868-1900.jpg', alt='Florida flag from 1868')
          h4 1868–1900
          p Adopted during the Reconstruction at the same time as the Florida state seal.
        li.flag-item
          span.flag: img.border(src='/assets/images/flag-florida-1900-1985.jpg', alt='Florida flag from 1900')
          h4 1900–1985
          p The red saltire is added by Governor Francis P. Fleming.
        li.flag-item
          span.flag: img.border(src='/assets/images/flag-florida.svg', alt='current Florida flag')
          h4 1985–Present
          p The seal and flag undergo revisions. The current flag of Florida.

